UI choices for tools

Christine Stawitz

ECS Federal in support of NOAA Fisheries

April 9, 2020

Outline

  • Tiered architecture
  • Text interface
  • Form interface
  • Graphical user interface

Results of survey

For FIT

  • Tiers can be considered to be data, model, UI
  • Modularity is key
  • Enables privacy of data within public models and UI
  • Enables different use cases for models (e.g. batch simulations with command line, GUI for novice users)

Text based

Command line

Pros

  • Fastest

  • Good for batch processing

  • Least work for developer

Cons

  • Harder to use

  • Syntax changes between OS

Programmatic

Pros

  • Customizable

  • Most modular

Cons

  • Requires language knowledge

  • Hard to ensure reliability and consistency

Form interface

Form interface

Pros

  • Can be auto-generated

  • Ensure consistent input

Cons

  • Less dynamic

  • Filling out form can be time consuming

GUI

GUI

Pros

  • Easiest to use
  • Most foolproof for users
  • Can be used by managers

Cons

  • Harder to automate
  • Most time-consuming to make

Desktop app

  • Requires install permissions
  • Can be more performant

Shiny with R

  • Natively write using R code
  • Extensible with custom html and js
  • Less portable and can be slow

html

  • Requires some knowledge
  • Web standard
  • Easier to use tiers

Takeaways

  • Please use tiered architecture!
  • GUI helpful for teaching and managers
  • Time in creating a GUI
  • Many scientists prefer programmatic interfaces for customization
